summary: James Best was best known for his portrayal of bumbling sheriff Rosco P. Coltrane on TV's "The Dukes of Hazzard" He died in hospice in Hickory, North Carolina, of complications from pneumonia, a friend says. "I laughed and learned more from Jimmie in one hour than from anyone else in a whole year," John Schneider says.

Dr. Anthony Moschetto faces criminal solicitation, conspiracy, burglary, arson, criminal prescription sale and weapons charges. He was released after posting $2 million bond and surrendering his passport. Two other men -- identified as accomplices -- have pleaded not guilty in Nassau County District Court.

President Obama says climate change is a public health issue that affects all of us. Obama encourages ordinary citizens, doctors and nurses to start putting some pressure on elected officials. Obama did not appear particularly concerned about the current Supreme Court challenge to the Affordable Care Act. The average American can also do their part to reduce their own carbon footprint.

A Russian TV channel aired Hillary Clinton's first campaign video with a rating stamp that means it's for mature audiences. A clip of the video, which features a gay couple holding hands, got the 18+ rating from the independent TV Rain channel in Russia on Monday. The channel told CNN that it didn't want to break the controversial law, which bans "propaganda of nontraditional sexual relations around minors"

Ruben Navarrette: Marco Rubio has been his own worst enemy on two signature issues. He says Rubio has missed an opportunity to set himself apart from most of the presumptive Republican presidential candidates. He also says Rubio's political philosophy will be a tough sell to Hispanics. Navarrete: Rubio is positioning himself as the next generation of GOP leadership.

"Orphan Black" returns for its second season on Saturday. "Turn: Washington's Spies" returns with a new subtitle and a new Monday night time slot. "Veep" adds Hugh Laurie and Julia Louis-Dreyfus is now the president of the United States.

"I'm inside a plane and I feel like it's up moving in the air," the caller says. "There could be a person in there so we're going to come back around," the pilot tells air traffic control. The ramp agent is an employee of Menzies Aviation, a contractor for Alaska Airlines.

Mullah Mohammed Omar is credited with founding the Taliban in the early 1990s. The Taliban's "Cultural Commission" released the 11-page document on the movement's website. Several Afghan observers say the biography is aimed at dispelling rumors of Omar's demise. "There have been a lot of rumors lately about him. Some people are saying that he is not alive," one says.

CNN confirms that Michelle MacLaren is leaving the upcoming "Wonder Woman" movie. The movie, starring Gal Gadot in the title role of the Amazon princess, is still set for release on June 23, 2017. It's the first theatrical movie centering around the most popular female superhero.

British police say they knew a burglar alarm went off but didn't respond. The theft was so big that police haven't come up with a value for what was stolen. A former police official in London has speculated that the loss could run to £200 million, or $300 million.

Toya Graham says she wasn't concerned that she might be embarrassing her son. "He was embarrassing himself by wearing that mask and that hoodie and doing what he was doing," she says. The video of Graham yanking her son, Michael Singleton, from a protest has led to the Internet calling Graham #motheroftheyear.

In Neolithic times trepanation -- or drilling a hole into the skull -- was thought to be a cure for everything from epilepsy to migraines. The implement often used to carry out the primitive surgery was made from one of the sharpest substances found in nature -- obsidian. Obsidian -- a type of volcanic glass -- can produce cutting edges many times finer than even the best steel scalpels.

A Saudi general says the coalition has undertaken 1,200 airstrikes since March 26. Clashes took place Friday near the Saudi-Yemeni border, in the Najran region. Yemen has been descending into chaos since Houthi rebels forced Yemeni President Abdu Rabu Mansour Hadi from power.

A new CNN/ORC poll finds 57% feel businesses such as caterers or florists should be required to serve gay or lesbian couples just as they would heterosexual couples. 41% say they should be allowed to refuse service for religious reasons. That's a shift from a Pew Research Center poll conducted last fall.

James Holmes is accused of killing 12 people and injuring or maiming 70 others in 2012. Opening statements in his trial are scheduled to begin Monday. Holmes says he was insane at the time of the shootings, and that is his legal defense and court plea. Prosecutors aren't swayed and will seek the death penalty.

Up to 200 people are feared missing after a landslide in a trekking area north of Kathmandu. The death toll has now climbed above 4,600 in Nepal, officials say. Rescue efforts are hampered by problems of getting aid into the country and delivering it to some of the remote communities.

Frida Ghitis: We set Baltimore on fire, brutalized black bodies, turned a funeral into a riot. She says the word "we" is one of the great American words: We the People. Ghitis says both longstanding structural racism and personal irresponsibility are on display this week. She writes: We cannot separate out the aspects of the problem that don't fit our preferred explanation.

Indiana's new religious freedom law has sparked controversy. Critics say it is an invitation for businesses to discriminate against gays and lesbians. Supporters say the law is basically a copy of a federal law that is already in the books at the federal level and 19 other states. Here are five things you might not have considered when thinking about this controversy.

Six survivors of the Paris kosher supermarket siege in January are suing a French media outlet. The media outlet, CNN affiliate BFMTV, is accused of endangering the lives of the hostages. Gunman Amedy Coulibaly stormed the Hyper Cacher Jewish supermarket on January 9, killing four people.

Walter Scott was killed in North Charleston after getting pulled over for a broken taillight. Officer Michael Slager was swiftly charged with murder and faces life in prison or the death penalty if convicted. A witness says she saw Scott and Slager scuffling at the entrance to a vacant lot.

Enoch Gaver, 21, was killed in the fight in the town of Cottonwood, Arizona. Police Sergeant Jeremy Daniels was hit in the leg by a bullet fired during the melee. At least three members of the family are reportedly in a Christian band named "Matthew 24 Now"

Ringo Starr is the final Beatle to be inducted as a solo act. Joan Jett & the Blackhearts were inducted in her own inimitable way. Fall Out Boy gave one of the two most exciting performances of the evening. It was a night for the young to honor the old and perhaps prepare for a later visit.

Daniel Boykin, 33, entered the woman's home multiple times, where he took videos, photos and other data. Police found more than 90 videos and 1,500 photos of the victim on Boykin's phone and computer. The victim filed a complaint after seeing images of herself on his phone last year.

In 2003, less than 30% of religiously affiliated Americans supported gays' and lesbians' right to wed. By 2014, that number had climbed to 47%, according to a survey conducted by the Public Religion Research Institute. The margin is small but statistically significant, because of the exceptionally large pool of respondents: 40,000 adult Americans.

Hatton Garden Safe Deposit Ltd. was robbed over the Easter weekend, police say. About 60-70 safe deposit boxes were opened during the burglary, they say. Hatton Garden is a storied area in London and the heart of the city's diamond trade. Many of those who rent boxes at the company are reportedly in the jewelry trade.

Students stampeded down the halls of a dormitory and some jumped from its fifth floor. Hundreds were injured and were taken to hospitals. The confusion and panic came less than two weeks after Al-Shabaab slaughtered 147 people at a college in Garissa. Kenyan teachers and students have said they fear being targeted by the Somalia-based terrorists.

"Operation Renewal of Hope" will focus on the political process. Saudi Arabia had launched airstrikes on Houthi positions across Yemen. The Saudis say they want to restore the Yemeni government, a key U.S. ally. Ousted Yemen President Abdu Rabu Mansour Hadi thanked the Saudi-led coalition.

CNN goes to "unofficial" displaced camp in Yola, Nigeria, to find children to "foster" The camp is one of the many that has mushroomed in the town of Yola as the influx of people fleeing Boko Haram has grown. The Global Slavery Index says Nigeria has the highest number of people in modern slavery of any sub-Saharan country.

Diana, Princess of Wales, is the sentimental favorite among punters for the royal baby's name. The name conjures up both positive and negative responses the world over. The Queen was very fond of Diana, but should her name be bestowed as a first name upon the baby it would be perceived as a slap in the face to the monarchy.

Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, was once known as the murder capital of the world. At the height of cartel violence, the city averaged 8.5 killings per day. But five years later, local officials say the city is much safer, and plans are underway to lure foreign tourists and investors back to Juarez.

Officer Michael Rapiejko says he thought he was too far to take a shot at Mario Valencia. The Marana, Arizona, police officer hit Valencia with his patrol car in February. Valencia, who flew through the air, survived and faces more than a dozen charges for an alleged crime spree.

Cape Verde is seeking to tap-into the spoils of its rich cultural heritage to help its economy flourish. The former Portuguese territory was once a key location for the transatlantic slave trade. The Atlantic Music Expo is a three-year-old conference and networking event that seeks to help Cape Verdean artists secure international exposure.

On Kabul's streets, you can easily find the uneasy legacy of America's longest war. Vast supply chains once kept 120,000 troops fed and watered. Trucks that once supplied millions sit still. One road, forever pot-holed in the past decade, is now being covered over by Afghans.

The P5+1 reached a framework agreement with Iran over the country's nuclear program. The parties have until the end to June to work out the details and put the plan to paper. But the talks this week were, nevertheless, historic, particularly for the otherwise frozen U.S.-Iranian relationship.

A swarm of Asian carp attacked the Washington University of rowing team. No rowers were injured, but the strong smell of fish lingered in the moments afterward. Watch iReporter Benjamin Rosenbaum's video of the incident in the player below. The incident occurred early Friday morning.

The flight data recorder, or "black box," was found Thursday by recovery teams. The French air accident investigation agency says its teams have begun to investigate its contents. A German official says Andreas Lubitz's actions amount to "premeditated murder" German prosecutors say a tablet found at his apartment shows he researched suicide methods.

The video shows an initial traffic stop and early interactions between the officer and Scott. It's not clear whether Scott took the officer's Taser or whether the officer picked the object up and moved it closer to the body. Officer Michael Slager has been fired and charged with murder.

5-year-old Doberman ate watch heads, leather straps and metal pieces. Mocha was a repeat offender; she had emergency stomach surgery last summer. Veterinarians removed about a pound of leather straps, metal pieces and detritus. Owner: "It just looked like a Christmas tree and I almost threw up"

Tuesday's power outage triggered a burst of wild conspiracy theories across social media. There is fertile ground for rumor-mongering in Turkey. Heavy-handed censorship has left the mainstream media widely distrusted. And the absence of a common, credible space for sharing information has pushed critics of the government to the fringes of the social media fringes.

Al Qaeda fighters attack a prison in the coastal Yemeni city of Al Mukallah. At least 270 prisoners, a third of whom have al Qaeda links, are freed. Dozens of attackers take control of government buildings, including the Central Prison, Central Bank and radio station. Yemen has been descending into chaos in the weeks since Shiite Houthi rebels removed Hadi from power.

Ines Dumig's photo series "Apart Together" features Somali refugee Sahra. Dumig met Sahra through a photo workshop at Refugio, a shelter in Munich, Germany. The underlying themes of the series include feelings of isolation and "otherness" and the search for a valuable human dignity.

A group of 10 doctors from across the country emailed a letter to Columbia University expressing disapproval that Oz is on the faculty. They accuse Oz of what they call "manifesting an egregious lack of integrity" in his TV and promotional work. In a written statement issued last week, Oz said he will address the issue on his show next week.

Volvo says it will begin exporting vehicles made in a factory in southwest China to the United States next month. It will be the first time Chinese-built passenger cars will roll into American showrooms. CEO Håkan Samuelsson said Volvo planned to sell 1,500 Chinese-made S60 Inscription sedans in 2015 and 5,000 annually in subsequent years.

NASA's New Horizons spacecraft has sent back its first color image of Pluto. The probe is due to make its closest approach to Pluto on July 14. Pluto is 1,400 miles wide, roughly half the width of the continental United States. At 3.6 billion miles out in the solar system, it's about 40 times as far as Earth is.

Paul Nungesser is suing Columbia University for allowing his accuser to publicly brand him a "serial rapist" He was cleared of responsibility in Emma Sulkowicz's 2013 rape claim, as well as others that came to light after she went public with her allegations in various media interviews. Her case drew national attention after she started carrying a mattress around campus.

Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, 21, faces life in prison or the death penalty for working with his brother to explode bombs at the 2013 Boston Marathon. The defense has maintained that Tsarnaev, who was 19 and flunking out of college at the University of Massachusetts, Dartmouth, fell under the sway of his brother.

Aaron Hernandez is found guilty of first-degree murder in the death of Odin Lloyd. Lloyd's body was found in an industrial park in North Attleboro, Massachusetts, in June 2013. Hernandez also faces murder charges in a 2012 double homicide; he has pleaded not guilty.

Japan's nuclear watchdog had previously given a green light to the reopening of reactors 3 and 4 of the Takahama nuclear plant. But locals successfully petitioned the court in Fukui Prefecture, raising concerns about whether the reactors would survive a strong earthquake. Japan's 48 nuclear reactors are offline in the wake of the Fukushima disaster in 2011.

Arsenal beat Burnley 1-0 at Turf Moor to stay second in the English Premier League. Aaron Ramsey scored the only goal of the game in the first half. The win takes Arsenal to within four points of first placed Chelsea. Chelsea have two games in hand and play lowly Queens Park Rangers on Sunday.

"The Americans" is one of the best series on TV. "Fresh Off the Boat" is the first sitcom with an Asian-American cast since the 1990s. "Scorpion," about a ragtag band of geniuses sent on secret missions, got a lot of hype.

Since civil war broke out there, 310,000 people have been killed, the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights says. A year earlier, SOHR's tally stood at 162,402. And the year before, the United Nations put the death toll at 70,000.

Feidin Santana says he was told by another cop to stop using his phone to capture the incident. "Mr. Scott never tried to fight," Santana tells CNN. In other interviews, Santana has said he feared for his life, which almost kept him from revealing the recording.

Freddie Gray died from a severe spinal cord injury, an autopsy says. Police say they spotted Gray, gave chase, caught him, cuffed him and requested a "wagon" to transport him. Protesters want to know exactly what happened in those 30 minutes, and say it's clear police used too much force.

The stars have teamed together for a video backing the show's co-creator. Lynch announced Sunday that he was exiting Showtime's nine-episode revival over a salary dispute. He originally signed on to direct the project but noted that there was "not enough money offered to do the script the way I felt needed to be done"

The world economy has expanded at least 100-fold since industrial capitalism first found its footing in Britain around 1800. The idea of sustainable development is that an economy must satisfy all three principles: economic growth, social fairness and environmental sustainability. Sustainable development is a doctrine that says: Let us once again place the economy on a true moral foundation and we'll keep greed within bounds.

Kenya's interior minister says four terrorists were killed and the operation ended "successfully" Hundreds of students managed to escape Garissa University College, a CNN affiliate reports. Al-Shabaab, the Somalia-based terror group that's claimed responsibility for the attack, has made bloody incursions into Kenya.

The Sewol ferry sank on April 16, killing 304 people, mostly high school students. The divers stopped searching months ago because of the winter and water conditions. The process could take over a year and a half, and that it would cost the South Korean government anywhere from $91 million to $182 million.

scores of dead fish have appeared in the Rodrigo de Freitas lagoon in Rio de Janeiro. The city is preparing to host the 2016 Olympics. Officials believe the recent rains caused a temperature change of the water and the excess of decaying organic matter, which would have led to a black of oxygen.

"He was outgoing -- loved everybody, (was) very known in the community," his brother says. At the time of his death, Walter Scott owed over $18,000 in back payments for two children. "He was not a dangerous person," a family lawyer says of Scott's legal history.

U.S. prosecutions of would-be recruits to ISIS have exploded. The flurry of arrests is a sign that complicated, manpower-intensive investigations are finally being completed. But they also highlight the unique challenges that ISIS poses in comparison with al Qaeda, which has attracted fewer U.S.-based recruits.

Andreas Lubitz, the co-pilot on Germanwings Flight 9525, was diagnosed with depression. Peter Schmitz: It's curious to me how the red flags of his illness were missed. He says the selection process is most likely highly competitive, requiring above-average aptitude. Schmetz: Wouldn't a manager consider a candidate with an indication of potential issues?

For Koreans, drinking is considered a way to get to know what someone is really like. Koreans always identify the "higher" person in the relationship, and defer to them accordingly. It's considered rude for anyone to have an empty glass. Koreans love singing, and karaoke bars are the most popular venues.

Alondra Luna Nuñez, 14, was taken from her middle school in Guanajuato, central Mexico. She was believed to be the daughter of a Mexican national living in Houston. A woman in Houston claimed in a 2007 petition that her daughter had been illegally taken to Mexico.

Coroner's preliminary assessment is there was no foul play involved in the death. Andrew Getty, 47, had "several health issues," police say. He is the grandson of oil tycoon J. Paul Getty, who died in 1976. Gordon Getty spearheaded the controversial sale of Getty to Texaco for $10 billion in 1984.

Nearly 60% of the people in America's workforce are paid hourly and work part-time. Congress should help low-wage workers gain access to predictable work schedules, authors say. "Just-in-time" scheduling creates unstable and stressful work environments, they say.

Frida Ghitis: The Supreme Court seems to have increasingly become a place for partisan theatrics. She says the marriage equality arguments seemed even more shaped by politics than the law. Ghitis says the court's also clear is the court has evolved from reason and submissive politics to politics.

Ayatollah Khomeini famously said he was "drinking poison" when he accepted a ceasefire to end the eight-year-old war with Iraq. Like the war, Iran's defiance to halt its controversial nuclear program has defined Ayatollah Ali Khamenei's era. The standoff with the West has stretched longer than the war.

Iranian President Hassan Rouhani has praised the military as peacemakers for the Middle East. The country's top military brass seemed surprisingly relaxed and unusually willing to speak with Western media outlets. The U.S. welcomes some of Iran's support for Iraqi forces in the fight against ISIS, but says there simply is no basis for deeper cooperation on the battlefield.

ABC is filming a proof of concept for a revival of "The Muppets" Bill Prady is co-writing the script for a pilot presentation that could be unspooled at May's upfront presentation to advertisers. Sources tell THR that the project, if all goes well, could go straight to series.

Jean Nidetch started Weight Watchers with a group of friends in 1961. She lost 72 pounds and inspired millions more to shed pounds too. "It's choice -- not chance -- that determines your destiny," she said. "Jean was an inspiration and an innovator," CEO says.

Jerome R. Hunt, 54, of Hayward, California, climbed the fence on the south side of the White House complex. Hunt is in custody and charges are pending. The package was being examined and later deemed to be harmless, a Secret Service source says. The Secret Service has come under heavy criticism after two incidents compromised the security of the grounds.

Robert Boardwine's friend used his sperm and a turkey baster to get pregnant. She thought because they never had sex, she was entitled to be the boy's sole parent. Boardwine argued that he always expected to be a dad, going to the kid's games.

Nyia Parler, 41, cannot be extradited to face charges in Philadelphia until she completes an unspecified "treatment," Maryland police say. A man walking through the woods found him Friday "lying in leaves, covered in a blanket with a Bible and a wheelchair nearby" Parler's sister told police that Parler has another child, a 16-year-old.

The James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) will launch in October 2018. It is intended as the successor to the Hubble instrument that has been operating in space for 25 years. JWST will work in the infra-red spectrum, allowing scientists to detect more distant targets. NASA says the mission will cost $8.5 billion.

Ailina Tsarnaeva is the sister of Dzhokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev. Authorities allege the brothers are responsible for the 2013 Boston marathon bombing. The Tsarnaev family first immigrated to the Boston area back in 2002. The parents, fleeing a troubled region of Russia, were treated as legal residents and granted asylum.

A year ago, more than 200 Nigerian schoolgirls were snatched from their boarding school dormitories in the dead of night in Chibok, northeastern Nigeria. In the early days of their abduction much of the world stood as one, rallying around the hashtag #BringBackOurGirls. "Injustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere," says Martin Luther King.

Mohamed Morsy is convicted on charges of violence and inciting violence. He is sentenced to 20 years in prison for the torture of protesters outside the presidential palace. But he is acquitted of murder in the deaths of protesters. His party calls the trial a "travesty of justice"

Sandra Mackey predicted events that unfolded in the Middle East well before they happened. Her book on Iraq became required reading for many military leaders trying to understand the country. Mackey was a frequent commentator on CNN during the Gulf War in the 1990s. She also appeared on countless other outlets, including Bill Maher's "Politically Incorrect"

Polish Prince challenges UKIP leader Nigel Farage to a duel in London's Hyde Park. Prince Jan Zylinski says he is fed up with discrimination against Poles living in Britain. Farage complains that Britain's membership of the European Union means it is powerless to stop a flow of foreign immigrants.

Photographer Timothy Bouldry captures what it's like to live inside a landfill in India. The Boragaon landfill is located in the city of Guwahati, about 300 miles from Bangladesh. About 100 families live inside the landfill and make around $2 per day.

Hospital gowns are among the most vexing parts of being in the hospital. The Cleveland Clinic was an early trendsetter, introducing new gowns in 2010. It's all part of a trend among hospitals to improve the patient reviews and their own bottom lines. But replacing the traditional design is no easy task.

Dr. Anthony Moschetto, 54, pleads not guilty to criminal solicitation, conspiracy, burglary, arson, criminal prescription sale and weapons charges. He was released after posting $2 million bond and surrendering his passport. Two other men -- identified as James Chmela, 43, and James Kalamaras, 41 -- were named as accomplices.

Joy Womack was one of the first Americans accepted into the Bolshoi Ballet Academy. In 2013 she left under a cloud -- media reports suggested she had claimed she was asked by an unnamed Boshoi official to pay $10,000 to dance in even small roles. The dancer, raised in California and Texas, left her parents and eight brothers and sisters behind when she arrived in Russia.

YouTuber Bobby Burns created a fan version of the "Batman v. Superman" trailer. The 18-year-old used classic superhero footage to make the video. He says he wanted to contrast the old with the new. The reaction to the video has been great, Burns says.

CNN's John Sutter says he sees signs of a medical marijuana revolution everywhere. For the first time a majority, 53%, favor its legalization, he says. Support for legalization has risen 11 points in the past few years alone. Sutter: "Weed 3" will be the first federally approved clinical study on the use of marijuana for PTSD.

Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, 21, has been found guilty on every count in the Boston Marathon bombings. He faces life in prison if convicted of all charges. On Tuesday, jurors heard about the holes his bombs left in the hearts of the survivors and the families of the dead. "Krystle was the light of my life," a father says.

A draft script of the 1985 teen classic has just been found in a filing cabinet in the school district where it was filmed. The manuscript sports the approval signature of the district's then-superintendent. Molly Ringwald's character, Claire Standish, was originally to be named Cathy Douglas.

A NASA astrophysicist has named an asteroid after Malala Yousafzai. She was gravely wounded by a Pakistani Taliban gunman for promoting the right of girls' to go to school. The asteroid circles the sun between Mars and Jupiter every five and half years. It is about 4 kilometers in diameter, and its surface is very dark.

The Supreme Court will hear oral arguments Tuesday in a case that could decide whether gay and lesbian couples have the constitutional right to marry. Chief Justice John Roberts has a solid conservative record and would seem an unlikely vote to support a right to same-sex marriage. Both sides see the case as a legacy-making moment for the 60-year-old chief justice.

Of the ship's 2,117 passengers, 95 have suffered from vomiting, diarrhea and other symptoms. The illness has also affected five members of the 964-person crew. The CDC has yet to determine what's causing the ailments. The Infinity left San Diego on March 29 and made its last stop in Puerto Vallarta, Mexico.

Three of the teens have been released "pending further enquiries," police say. The suspects planned to attack during a major national commemoration in a week, Prime Minister Tony Abbott says. Police: The suspects were associates of 18-year-old Nadun Haider, who was killed in September.

Yellowstone's magma reserves are many magnitudes greater than previously thought. Underneath the national park's attractions and walking paths is enough hot rock to fill the Grand Canyon nearly 14 times over. An eruption in the next few thousand years is extremely unlikely, the USGS says.

The entire "Star Wars" saga will be released on digital HD at the end of the week. "Dukes of Hazzard" fans mourned the loss of actor James Best. Michelle Obama brought the White House down with the "So You Think You Can Dance" all-stars.

Kamron Taylor, 23, was convicted of murder in February. On Wednesday, he attacked a correctional officer outside his cell, authorities say. He then got into the officer's car and drove away. A $5,000 reward is being offered for information leading to his arrest.

Andrew Getty, 47, was found on his side near a bathroom in his home, KTLA reports. A female friend was at the home where Getty died and is cooperating with investigators, police say. Court records show Andrew Getty had recently filed to get a restraining order against a woman.

ISIS took thousands of Yazidis captive. Men faced a choice -- convert to Islam or be shot. But the Islamist militants separated the young women and girls to be sold as sex slaves. ISIS: Enslaving, having sex with 'unbelieving' women, girls is OK.

Robert Bates, 73, is accused of fatally shooting Eric Harris in April. He says he meant to subdue Harris with a Taser, but mistakenly shot him with a gun. A judge granted Bates permission to go to the Bahamas for a family vacation. That decision prompted a response from the family of the man Bates killed.

Special forces are on the ground in noncombat roles, a Saudi source says. Houthi rebels withdraw from the presidential palace and other key parts of Aden. The United Nations says 519 people have been killed and nearly 1,700 others wounded in the past two weeks.

CNN was granted rare access on a desperate aid mission by Unicef, the United Nations Children's Fund. More than 100,000 Yemeni civilians have fled their homes since fighting began. The main terminal at El Rahaba Airport is under the control of the Houthi rebels.

John T. Booker Jr. enlisted in the Army last year and was due to ship out to basic training April 7. A second man, who allegedly knew about the bomb plot but didn't call authorities, was charged with failing to report a felony. The "bomb" had actually been put together by two confidential informants with nonexplosive materials.

Gisele Bundchen announced her retirement from the catwalk last weekend. She is the face of Chanel and Carolina Herrera and has her own line of lingerie. "I want to be with my family more and focus on special projects," she said in an interview.

U.S. warships are being deployed to monitor ships traveling from Iran that could be trafficking arms to Houthi rebels in Yemen. The move was also meant to reassure allies in the region, a Pentagon spokesman said. President Barack Obama told MSNBC that the United States has been clear in its messages to Tehran.

Hillary Clinton's campaign-in-waiting met on Saturday in its Brooklyn headquarters, a Democrat who attended the meeting said. Robby Mook, Clinton's soon-to-be campaign manager, distributed a "values statement" The document makes clear that the campaign will try to avoid mistakes that plagued Clinton's failed 2008 run.

China's biggest auto show opens in Shanghai this week. Vehicle sales in China totaled 23.5 million units last year, almost a third more than in the United States. Intense competition for China's drivers means that car manufacturers are increasingly developing vehicles that cater to Chinese preferences.

Sarah Brady, 73, died of pneumonia, her family says. She and her husband, James Brady, pushed for stricter gun control laws. James Brady was shot in the head by John Hinckley Jr. during his attempt to assassinate Reagan in 1981. Brady spent the rest of his life in a wheelchair, advocating against gun violence.

"Galaxy Quest" is the latest movie to be adapted for the small screen. The film starred Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver, Alan Rickman, Tony Shalhoub, Sam Rockwell, Daryl Mitchell and Enrico Colantoni. Paramount Television specifically has turned several of the studio's hit films into TV series.

Keonna Thomas, 30, is charged with trying to travel overseas to fight for ISIS. She's one of three women arrested this week on terror charges. Two New York women were also taken into custody. In the past 18 months, the Justice Department has prosecuted or is prosecuting more than 30 cases of people attempting to travel abroad to join or provide support to terrorist groups.

Jared Leto will play the Joker in 2016's "Suicide Squad" The Oscar winner cut his hair and shaved his face for the role. He will be the first actor to play the character on the big screen since the late Heath Ledger. The movie hits theaters August 5, 2016.

No one was injured in the shooting, and no arrests have been made. Lil Wayne was in Atlanta for a performance at Compound nightclub Saturday night. Witnesses provided a limited description of the two vehicles suspected to be involved: a "Corvette style vehicle" and an SUV.

Ben Powers played Keith Anderson on the final season of "Good Times" He also had a regular role as "Moochie" on the CBS detective drama show. Powers died April 6 in New Bedford, Mass., his family announced. No cause of death was revealed.

Kurdish separatists opened fire from a long distance, CNN Turk reports. About a fifth of Turkey's population is Kurdish. The conflict has been, some say, a battle by activists among Turkey's Kurdish minority for independence. Since the first incidents more than three decades ago, an estimated 40,000 lives have been lost.

HBO has released a teaser video for season 2 of "True Detective" Colin Farrell, Vince Vaughn, Rachel McAdams and Taylor Kitsch star in the new season. The new season premieres June 21. The first season starred Matthew McConaughey and Woody Harrelson.

Carlos Colina, 32, was arraigned on charges of assault and battery causing serious bodily injury and improper disposal of a body. Police were notified Saturday morning about a suspicious item along a walkway in Cambridge. Officers arrived at the scene, opened a duffel bag and found human remains.

Anthony Doerr's "All the Light We Cannot See" wins the Pulitzer Prize for fiction. "Between Riverside and Crazy," a play by Stephen Adly Guirgis, wins for drama. Elizabeth Kolbert's "The Sixth Extinction: An Unnatural History" wins for general nonfiction.

The Statue of Liberty and Liberty Island will reopen to the public Saturday. A bomb threat that led to its evacuation was declared unfounded. The NYPD bomb squad examined a locker thought to contain a suspicious package and found it was empty. All civilians were evacuated and only emergency personnel remained on Liberty Island.

25-1 outsider Many Clouds wins the Grand National on Saturday. Jockey Leighton Aspell won last year's Grand National too. Owner Trevor Hemmings says it is his third Grand National win. AP McCoy's horse Shutthefrontdoor was heavily backed by the betting public.

Dr. Mehmet Oz has been accused of pushing "quack treatments ... for personal financial gain" Dr. John Oliver eviscerated Oz on his hit HBO show "Last Week Tonight" Oz and his producers responded with alacrity, slicing and dicing his ill-prepared challengers.

SkyWest Airlines Flight 5622 was originally scheduled to fly from Chicago to Hartford. The plane descended 28,000 feet in three minutes.
